â­ 3. Jenkins Webhook (CI Trigger)
â“ What is a webhook?

A webhook is a signal from GitHub to Jenkins saying:

â€œHey! New code was pushed. Start the pipeline now.â€

Without webhooks â†’ Jenkins must manually check GitHub.
With webhooks â†’ Jenkins instantly starts when code is updated.

â­ 4. Steps to Configure Webhook (Simple)
âœ” Step 1: In Jenkins

Inside your Jenkins job:

Open Configure

Go to Build Triggers

Tick:

GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling

âœ” Step 2: Get Jenkins webhook URL

Your Jenkins webhook URL is:

http://<public-ip>:8080/github-webhook/


(If you use localhost â†’ use ngrok)

âœ” Step 3: In GitHub

Open your repository

Go to Settings â†’ Webhooks

Click Add Webhook

Paste Jenkins URL:

http://<public-ip>:8080/github-webhook/


Select:

Content Type: application/json

Trigger: Just push events

Click Add Webhook

ğŸ‰ Now when you push to GitHub â†’ Jenkins automatically builds.
â­ 5. Jenkins Pipeline Script (Example)
pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/yourusername/yourrepo.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean install'
            }
        }

        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
            }
        }
    }

    post {
        success {
            mail to: 'developer@gmail.com',
                 subject: 'Build Successful',
                 body: 'Your Jenkins build passed successfully!'
        }

        failure {
            mail to: 'developer@gmail.com',
                 subject: 'Build Failed',
                 body: 'Your Jenkins build failed. Check console logs.'
        }
    }
}


This pipeline:

Pulls code from GitHub

Builds using Maven

Runs tests

Sends success/failure emails

â­ 6. Jenkins Email Notification Setup
âœ” Step 1: Install Email Plugin

Go to Manage Jenkins â†’ Manage Plugins

Install: Email Extension Plugin

âœ” Step 2: Configure SMTP

Go to:

Manage Jenkins â†’ Configure System

Scroll to Extended Email Notification

Enter:

SMTP Server: smtp.gmail.com

Port: 465 or 587

Use SSL: Yes

Username: Your gmail

App Password: (Required â€” not normal password)

âœ” Step 3: Add Default Recipients

Example:

dattagoud@gmail.com


Click Test Configuration â†’ You should receive a test email.

â­ 7. How Email Notifications Work in Pipeline

In the pipelineâ€™s post block:

post {
    success {
        mail to: 'team@gmail.com',
             subject: 'Build Success',
             body: 'Your Jenkins build completed without errors.'
    }
    failure {
        mail to: 'team@gmail.com',
             subject: 'Build Failed',
             body: 'Your Jenkins build failed. Please check logs.'
    }
}


So whenever your build:

passes â†’ sends "Success" email

fails â†’ sends "Failure" email

This is real CI/CD used in companies.

â­ 8. What to Say in Viva
â“ What is a webhook?

A webhook is an automatic trigger from GitHub to Jenkins whenever code is pushed.

â“ Why do we use webhooks?

To automatically start Jenkins pipelines without manual action.

â“ What is CI?

Automatically integrating and building code after every commit.

â“ What is CD?

